# Wave Orchestration

```
IRON LAW: NO TASK EXECUTION WITHOUT A GOVERNED PLAN AND CONFLICT DETECTION
```

## Purpose
Execute implementation tasks in dependency order, detect conflicts early, and
keep wave results reviewable. This host owns the execution dispatch contract.

## Workflow Outline
Read task state, group dependency-ordered waves, then execute every ready wave
in sequence during this same host run until a natural execution stop point
appears. Wave boundaries are internal scheduling boundaries, not operator
commands.

## Read Context
Run `slipway next --json` and read the task plan from the governed change bundle.

For codebase mapping, keep the coordinator context to `input_context.wave_plan`
and the bounded map metadata from `slipway next --json`. Do not read durable map
documents into the coordinator just to prepare task briefs. Instead, pass
`input_context.codebase_map_dir` and relevant `input_context.codebase_map_docs`
paths to task executors along with `input_context.codebase_map_status` and
`input_context.codebase_map_doc_states`.

The codebase-map relevance/staleness self-check is preserved: it is
relocated to executor-owned relevance/staleness self-check work, not removed.
`input_context.codebase_map_status` still reflects content presence, not scope
relevance, and the codebase-map relevance advisory fires for `populated` and
`partial`.
Each executor that uses map guidance must judge whether the referenced docs
match this task's scope before relying on them, and must report stale or
non-durable docs in `test_summary` or blocker evidence. For a `partial` map,
also inspect `input_context.codebase_map_doc_states` inside the executor-owned
self-check; any per-doc `scaffold_only`, `baseline`, or `missing` entry is
non-durable for that document. Populated is not the same as relevant; this
advisory never blocks execution by itself, but stale map usage is not acceptable
evidence.

Apply `slipway-coding-discipline` while splitting work: keep task scopes
minimal, prefer simple changes, and reject executor plans that broaden beyond
the governed objective.

## Read the Current Wave Plan
At `S2_IMPLEMENT`, read the current task-derived wave projection from
`input_context.wave_plan` in `slipway next --json`: `wave_count`, `total_tasks`,
and `waves[]` (each `wave_index` with `tasks[]` carrying `task_id`, `objective`,
`depends_on`, `target_files`, `task_kind`). Slipway has already dependency-ordered
the waves and detected cycles from the current `tasks.md`; do not re-derive a
separate grouping that could diverge from the engine projection. The persisted
`wave-plan.yaml` is an execution cache/audit artifact materialized from this
projection, not S1 planning authority. If `input_context.wave_plan.parse_error`
is set (for example, a dependency cycle or invalid task metadata), treat it as a
blocker and follow the named remediation rather than executing.

Report the wave plan before execution: description, total tasks, wave count,
and one row per wave with task IDs plus a 3-8 word build summary.

## Execute Waves
Execute waves in sequence within this single wave-orchestration host run. After a
wave passes its executor collection, changed-file safety check, task evidence
recording, and post-wave integration gate, immediately continue to the next
ready wave. Do not ask the operator to run `slipway run` merely to cross a
wave boundary. **Within a wave, dispatch every task concurrently by default.**
Wave planning already guarantees a wave's tasks are dependency-free and
file-disjoint, and `slipway next --json` marks such a wave `parallel: true` in
`input_context.wave_plan.waves[]`; do not serialize a `parallel: true` wave for
convenience. A `parallel: true` wave requires real executor subagent fan-out
where the runtime has a subagent or fresh-session primitive; same-context inline
execution is not an equivalent dispatch mode for a capable runtime. If a capable
runtime cannot spawn, wait, collect, parse, and close executor sessions, stop and
ask for operator direction instead of silently running the whole wave in the
coordinator context. Fall back to sequential only when the host genuinely lacks
concurrent executor support, and when you do, say so in the wave report and the
wave-orchestration verification `references` as
`dispatch_mode:wave=<wave_index>:degraded_sequential`, with the same fact in
`notes`, so the degradation stays visible. Notes/prose alone are
human-readable context and are not parsed as dispatch evidence. A `parallel:
false` wave (a single task, or `execution.parallelization: off`) runs
sequentially with nothing to note.

## Target/Changed-File Safety Model
Slipway dispatches a wave into a single shared worktree: executor agents edit
the current worktree directly and there is no per-executor git worktree
isolation. The only safety boundary inside a wave is each task's declared
`target_files`, made true by each executor's exhaustive `changed_files`. Keep
both accurate: an executor that writes outside its `target_files`, or two
parallel tasks that write the same file, can clobber each other in the shared
tree.

The engine signals, records, and gates on this model; it does not spawn or
execute agents (this host owns the dispatch). When the host's recorded evidence
is missing or violates the model, Slipway records an open blocker and the change
fails closed to rerun, review, and corrected evidence rather than advancing. The
four engine-enforced wave blockers are:
- `task_changed_file_scope_escape:<task_id>:<file>` — a task's recorded
  `changed_files` includes a path not covered by that task's `target_files`
  (post-result scope-escape audit). Fix `target_files` or the change, then
  re-record evidence.
- `parallel_wave_changed_file_overlap:<wave_index>:<file>:<tasks>` — two tasks
  in the same `parallel: true` wave recorded the same changed file. Sequential
  waves sharing a file are allowed; a parallel overlap must be handled by a
  scope/plan amendment before evidence is re-recorded.
- `dispatch_mode_absent_on_started_parallel_wave:<wave_index>` — a started
  parallel wave recorded no dispatch-mode evidence. The engine no longer infers
  parallel dispatch silently; you must record
  `dispatch_mode:wave=<wave_index>:parallel_subagents` (or
  `:degraded_sequential`) for the wave.
- `executor_agent_missing:<wave_index>:<task_id>` — a `parallel_subagents` wave
  is missing a per-task `executor_agent` handle reference. Record exactly one
  handle per planned task in the wave.

To stay clear of these gates, run a target-overlap PREFLIGHT before spawning a
`parallel: true` wave, then a post-result changed-file conflict check after.
Before spawning, compare the current wave's planned `target_files`: if any two
tasks overlap by exact path, path alias, parent/child scope, case-insensitive
match, or glob scope, do not spawn them in parallel. Record a host blocker such
as `dispatch_blocker:wave=<wave_index>:target_overlap` and stop for operator
direction before continuing. After executor results return, run the post-result changed-file
conflict check across returned `changed_files`; if parallel executors touched
the same file scope or escaped their declared target scope, record a post-result
changed-file conflict and do not run the integration gate or start the next wave
until it is resolved — this is the same condition the engine audits as
`parallel_wave_changed_file_overlap` and `task_changed_file_scope_escape`.

For each wave: describe the build goal before spawning, wait for all executors,
spot-check the first 2 files from each task's `changed_files`, check blocker
evidence, report what the wave enables next, and continue directly to the next
wave unless a natural stop point is reached.

Natural execution stop points:
- target-overlap preflight or post-result changed-file conflict makes parallel
  dispatch unsafe
- executor spawn, wait, result parsing, or handle cleanup fails
- post-wave integration gate fails or times out
- task evidence cannot be recorded through `slipway evidence task`
- every planned wave has completed and review should begin

## Post-Wave Integration Gate
Before starting the next wave, run a post-wave integration gate against the
merged current worktree. For any wave with `task_kind=code` or `task_kind=test`,
run the narrowest meaningful build/test command that can catch cross-task
integration failures; if the safe target is unclear, run the repository's normal
build/test suite. For docs/config/ops-only waves, run the relevant formatter,
lint, validation, or state why no executable gate exists. If the gate fails or
times out, record a blocker and do not start the next wave until the failure is
fixed or the user explicitly redirects. Passing per-task self-checks are not a
substitute for this post-wave integration gate. Do not run
shared-worktree-wide integration commands such as `go build ./...` concurrently
inside each task executor; leave merged-state build/test/lint checks to this
gate unless a task owns a genuinely isolated command.

## Dispatch Contract
- Dispatch one fresh-context executor subagent per task concurrently for a `parallel: true` wave; run sequentially only for a `parallel: false` wave or when the host genuinely cannot run concurrent executors (note that degradation, as above).
- For a capable runtime, failing to spawn real executors for `parallel: true` is a blocker or operator-direction point, not permission for same-context inline execution.
- Executor agents run in a single worktree unless a runtime explicitly provides stronger isolation; do not claim per-executor worktree isolation.
- Before spawn, perform the target-overlap preflight against the current wave's `target_files`; stop for operator direction on overlap instead of parallelizing unsafe writes.
- After results, perform the post-result changed-file conflict check before integration.
- Record dispatch references for successful fan-out: `dispatch_mode:wave=<wave_index>:parallel_subagents` plus one `executor_agent:wave=<wave_index>:task=<task_id>:<handle>` per spawned task.
- If an executor handle is lost, no parseable result returns, or waiting stalls, record `executor_handle_lost`, `executor_result_missing`, or `executor_dispatch_stalled` with known handles and last observed state; ask for operator direction and do not inline or mark the task complete without explicit authorization.
- Pass file paths only; executors read source files in their own context.
- Inputs: task ID, acceptance criteria, changed-file scope, technique references, locked decisions.
- For tasks that may need repository-map guidance, pass `input_context.codebase_map_dir` and relevant `input_context.codebase_map_docs` paths instead of inlining map content.
- Pass `input_context.codebase_map_doc_states` whenever map metadata is present so executors can perform the codebase-map relevance/staleness self-check.
- Outputs: `task_id`, `verdict`, `changed_files`, `test_summary`, `evidence_ref`, `blockers`, and concise `notes`.
- Write scopes must be disjoint, or the brief must name the merge strategy.
- For test-bearing work, isolate the `task_kind=test` test-authoring step from
  the `task_kind=code` implementation step: give the test-authoring executor
  only the spec, acceptance criteria, and public API signatures, never the implementation;
  freeze those tests before dispatching the later implementation task that names
  the test task in `depends_on`.
- For `task_kind=code`, enforce RED, then GREEN, then REFACTOR before accepting the result.
- Detailed dispatch examples live in `references/executor-dispatch-reference.md`.

## Task Evidence Ledger
For every completed task, record runtime task evidence through the supported CLI
before passing wave-orchestration. Do not hand-write files under
`.git/slipway/runtime/changes/<slug>/evidence/tasks/`.

```bash
slipway evidence task --task-id "<task_id>" --run-summary-version "<run_version>" --task-kind "<task_kind>" --verdict pass --evidence-ref "<transcript-or-command-ref>" --changed-file "<path>" --target-file "<path>" --json
```

Use `--blocker <code[:detail]>` and a non-pass `--verdict` when a task is not
complete. Slipway computes `freshness_inputs` and `captured_at` unless
`--captured-at` is explicitly provided. A passing wave-orchestration record
without task evidence blocks execution-summary generation.
Executor agents may report evidence refs, but the coordinator records them
through `slipway evidence task`; executors must not self-stamp governed
freshness or write verification YAML directly.

**Completeness contract:** record passing evidence for EVERY planned task in the
wave plan before the change can advance to review. A planned task left without
passing evidence blocks advancement with `incomplete_execution_task:<task_id>` —
partial execution does not reach S3_REVIEW. To intentionally drop a task, record
a same-intent scope amendment in `tasks.md` so the wave plan no longer claims it;
never skip its evidence.

## Guardrails
- The orchestrator stays below 15% of context budget. Do not read task source files just to "help."
- Auto-fix only issues directly blocking the current task and directly caused by the current task's change.
- After 3 auto-fix attempts on one task, stop and surface the blocker.
- Architectural change needed: stop, write a blocker, and wait for user direction.
- Spec or artifact blockers must use `spec:<artifact_id>` references.

## Write Verification
Use one current wave-orchestration `run_version` consistently for the task
evidence ledger and this verification record. If refreshing an earlier execution
run, do not reuse a stale literal value; choose the refreshed run_version and
record every task with that same value.

```yaml
# Write to: artifacts/changes/{slug}/verification/wave-orchestration.yaml
verdict: pass
blockers: []
timestamp: "<ISO-8601-UTC>"
run_version: <current wave-orchestration run_version>
references: []
notes: |
  <verification notes>
```

References should include the task evidence command outputs or stable refs for
each recorded task. For successful `parallel: true` fan-out, include a
structured dispatch reference and one executor handle reference per planned
task:

```yaml
references:
  - dispatch_mode:wave=<wave_index>:parallel_subagents
  - executor_agent:wave=<wave_index>:task=<task_id>:<handle>
```

If any `parallel: true` wave degraded to sequential because the host lacked
concurrent executors, include one structured reference per affected wave. A bare
`degraded_sequential` is no longer self-sufficient: the dispatch gate REQUIRES it
to be PAIRED with a genuine tool-unavailable justification for the same wave,
recorded as
`degraded_dispatch_justification:wave=<wave_index>:tool_unavailable=<detail>`,
where `<detail>` names why concurrent executor dispatch was unavailable on this
host:

```yaml
references:
  - dispatch_mode:wave=<wave_index>:degraded_sequential
  - degraded_dispatch_justification:wave=<wave_index>:tool_unavailable=<detail>
```

An unpaired `degraded_sequential` is rejected with
`degraded_dispatch_justification_missing` on standard/strict (advisory on light),
and the gate fires on every path that synchronizes governed wave execution,
including the `slipway evidence skill` path — not only advance/next. Recovery:
re-record the wave-orchestration evidence with the justification reference (or
re-run the wave with real concurrent dispatch). Do not fabricate the justification
when concurrent executors were actually available.

## Present and Advance
Show one execution summary for the full continuous S2 run, including every wave
attempted and every natural stop point encountered. {{template "hard-gate"}}
When all planned waves have passing task evidence and the wave-orchestration
verification record is written, run `slipway implement` or `slipway run` once to
let the lifecycle advance to S3_REVIEW. Do not call an advancing command between
wave boundaries; wave-to-wave continuation belongs to this host run.

## DO NOT SKIP
1. Dependency ordering before execution.
2. The target-overlap preflight before spawning a `parallel: true` wave.
3. Per-task executor handle references for spawned tasks.
4. File conflict detection after each wave, including the post-result changed-file conflict check.
5. Post-wave integration gate before starting the next wave.
6. Runtime task evidence via `slipway evidence task`.
7. Post-execution verification.

## Block If
- Dependency ordering is incomplete or cyclic.
- File conflicts remain unresolved after a wave.
- The post-wave integration gate fails, times out, or is skipped without a
  recorded no-executable-gate rationale.
- The target-overlap preflight finds unsafe single worktree overlap.
- A spawned executor loses its handle, returns no parseable result, or stalls
  without an explicit operator recovery decision.
- Retry budget is exhausted.
- Task evidence was not recorded through the supported CLI.
- Any planned task lacks passing evidence (`incomplete_execution_task`) and has
  not been removed by rescoping `tasks.md`.
